[SkillPath "bidding_conventions/stayman"]
[Student "S"]
{South opens 1NT.  

Even when you hold a 6-card Major, if you have 4 cards in the other Major you use Stayman. Partner answers 2\S.  

You've found an 8-card Major fit and you know there are enough points for game. So you bid 4\S.

Yes, but you already knew you had an 8-card \H fit since partner's 1NT promised at least 2 \Hs. In fact, you could play game in either Major. However, it is often better to play in a 4-4 fit rather than a 5-3 or 6-2. This hand shows why. Played in \Hs you will make exactly 10 tricks with any opening lead. Played in \Ss you will again make 10 tricks when the defenders start with their 3 \C winners. If they start with anything else you are very likely to make 1 or 2 overtricks by discarding dummy losers on your \H suit.}

